# Experiment 2 — Two-Particle Sequential Correlation

## Objective

Test whether a second particle, travelling very close in time to a measured first particle, shows path correlation without being directly measured for path.

---

## Core Idea

Particle A is measured.

Particle B is not measured.

If both particles are close enough in time within the same apparatus, Particle B may behave as if it has access to path information from Particle A.

This is not necessarily entanglement-based unless the particles are prepared in a shared entangled state. In this experiment, the focus is sequential temporal proximity.

---

## Experimental Setup

1. Emit Particle A.
2. Particle A passes through:

   - First double slit
   - Which-path detector ON

3. Record Particle A’s first outcome:

   - L₁ᴀ or R₁ᴀ

4. Emit Particle B shortly after Particle A.

5. Timing is controlled so Particle A and Particle B are close in time within the apparatus.

6. For Particle B:

   - Which-path detector is OFF

7. Both particles propagate through the second double slit.

> The second double slit must be physically identical to the first double slit within experimental tolerance.

8. Final detection records:

   - Particle A: L₂ᴀ or R₂ᴀ
   - Particle B: L₂ʙ or R₂ʙ

---

## Outcomes to Record

For each pair:

- Particle A first slit outcome: L₁ᴀ or R₁ᴀ
- Particle A second slit outcome: L₂ᴀ or R₂ᴀ
- Particle B second slit outcome: L₂ʙ or R₂ʙ
- Time separation Δt between A and B

---

## Correlation Analysis

Measure:

- P(L₂ʙ | L₂ᴀ)
- P(R₂ʙ | R₂ᴀ)
- P(L₂ʙ | L₁ᴀ)
- P(R₂ʙ | R₁ᴀ)

Also test whether correlation strength changes as Δt changes.

---

## Standard Quantum Mechanics Prediction

If Particle A and Particle B are independently prepared and not entangled:

- Particle B should behave independently.
- Particle B should not inherit which-path information from Particle A.
- Any observed correlation should be explainable by apparatus effects, detector memory, environmental disturbance, or statistical fluctuation.

Expected:

- P(L₂ʙ | L₂ᴀ) ≈ 50%
- P(R₂ʙ | R₂ᴀ) ≈ 50%

---

## Inter-Particle Correlation Prediction

The hypothesis predicts path-following behaviour:

- P(L₂ʙ | L₂ᴀ) > 50%
- P(R₂ʙ | R₂ᴀ) > 50%

If the effect is real, it may:

- Increase when Δt is smaller
- Decrease when particles are separated further in time
- Disappear when detector memory and apparatus persistence are eliminated

---

## Key Test

The critical test is whether Particle B shows statistically significant path correlation with Particle A when Particle B has no direct which-path measurement.

---

# Experiment 3 — Entanglement-Based Influence with Only One Particle Observed

## Objective

Test whether which-path measurement on one particle influences the standalone distribution of its entangled partner.

---

## Core Clarification

This experiment uses true entanglement.

Unlike Experiment 2, Particle A and Particle B are generated together as an entangled pair.

Particle A is measured for which-path.

Particle B is not measured for which-path.

Particle B still travels through the slit system and reaches the screen.

The question is not whether Particle B propagates. It does.

The key question is:

> Does Particle B show standalone bias without conditioning on Particle A?

---

## Experimental Setup

1. Generate an entangled particle pair:

   - Particle A
   - Particle B

2. Send Particle A through:

   - First double slit
   - Which-path detector ON

3. Record Particle A:

   - L₁ᴀ or R₁ᴀ

4. Send Particle B through:

   - Second double slit
   - No which-path detector

> The second double slit must be physically identical to the first double slit within experimental tolerance.

5. Record Particle B’s final detection position on the screen.

6. Analyse Particle B in two ways:

   - Unconditioned: ignore A’s result
   - Conditioned: group B results by A’s result

---

## Observables

### Unconditioned Distribution

Measure Particle B without referencing Particle A:

- P(L₂ʙ)
- P(R₂ʙ)

This is the most important test.

---

### Conditioned Distribution

Group Particle B results according to Particle A:

- P(L₂ʙ | L₁ᴀ)
- P(R₂ʙ | R₁ᴀ)

---

## Standard Quantum Mechanics Prediction

Standard quantum mechanics predicts:

- Particle B still reaches the screen.
- Particle B does not show standalone controllable bias.
- Correlations may appear only when B’s results are compared with A’s results.
- Looking at B alone should not reveal a signal from A’s measurement.

Expected unconditioned result:

- P(L₂ʙ) ≈ 50%
- P(R₂ʙ) ≈ 50%

Conditioned correlations may appear, but these are consistent with entanglement.

---

## Path Influence Prediction

The hypothesis predicts:

- Particle B shows unconditioned directional bias.
- This bias exists even before sorting by Particle A’s result.

Possible result:

- P(L₂ʙ) ≠ 50%
- P(R₂ʙ) ≠ 50%

This would suggest that measurement on Particle A influences the standalone statistics of Particle B.

---

## Critical Distinction

| Feature | Standard Quantum Mechanics | Proposed Hypothesis |
|---|---|---|
| Particle B reaches screen | Yes | Yes |
| B has standalone bias | No | Yes |
| B shows conditioned correlation with A | Yes | Yes |
| B can reveal A’s measurement without comparison | No | Possibly |

---

## Key Test

The key test is whether Particle B’s unconditioned distribution changes when Particle A is measured.

If Particle B only shows correlations after sorting by Particle A, that is standard quantum mechanics.

If Particle B shifts by itself, that would be non-standard.

---

# Experiment 4 — Measurement History Dependence / Sequential Conditioning

## Objective

Test whether the number or sequence of prior which-path measurements affects later outcomes after measurement stops.

---

## Core Idea

This is the “training” experiment.

A single particle passes through multiple observed double-slit stages, then later passes through another identical double slit with no observer.

The question is whether repeated observation reinforces a path tendency.

In stronger physics language:

> This experiment tests whether repeated projective measurements induce a persistent bias in subsequent unobserved evolution beyond standard state-update rules.

---

## Experimental Setup

### Conditioning Phase

1. Emit one particle.
2. Particle passes through N sequential double-slit stages, where N ≥ 1.
3. Each stage includes:

   - Physically identical double slit
   - Which-path detector ON
   - Recorded outcome

4. Record the sequence:

   - L₁, L₂, L₃, ... Lₙ
   - or R₁, R₂, R₃, ... Rₙ
   - or mixed sequences such as L-R-L-R

---

### Free Evolution Phase

5. After the conditioning stages, the particle passes through a final double slit.

> The final double slit must be physically identical to the previous slits within experimental tolerance.

6. The final double slit has:

   - No which-path detector
   - No observer
   - No weak marker

7. Record final outcome:

   - L_f
   - R_f

---

## Variables to Test

- Number of prior measurements N
- Sequence pattern:

  - LLLL
  - RRRR
  - LRLR
  - RRLL
  - Random mixed history

- Time between stages
- Distance between stages
- Detector strength during conditioning
- Whether final unobserved outcome changes with measurement history

---

## Standard Quantum Mechanics Prediction

Standard quantum mechanics predicts:

- Repeated measurement updates the state.
- The particle does not accumulate extra “training” beyond its current quantum state.
- Once measurement stops, future behaviour is governed by the current state and apparatus.
- Final distribution should not depend on the full measurement history in a way beyond standard state evolution.

Expected:

- P(L_f) ≈ 50%
- P(R_f) ≈ 50%

No scaling effect should appear purely from increasing N.

---

## Measurement History / Path Conditioning Prediction

The hypothesis predicts that prior measurement history affects later unobserved outcomes.

Possible outcomes:

- If prior history is mostly L:

  - P(L_f) > 50%

- If prior history is mostly R:

  - P(R_f) > 50%

- If N increases, the effect may strengthen.

- Different sequences may produce different final results:

  - LLLL may differ from LRLR
  - RRRR may differ from RRLL

---

## Critical Test

The critical test is:

> Does the final unobserved distribution vary as a function of measurement count N or prior sequence?

If no, the result supports standard quantum mechanics.

If yes, it suggests possible history-dependent behaviour.

---

# Apparatus Symmetry Requirement

This is critical.

All double-slit systems used in the experiments must be physically and functionally identical within experimental tolerance.

This includes:

- Slit width
- Slit separation
- Slit material
- Slit thickness
- Orientation
- Alignment
- Optical path length, except where deliberately varied
- Environmental exposure
- Detector placement
- Distance to final screen

---

## Why This Matters

Any observed bias must not be attributable to ordinary apparatus asymmetry.

Potential false explanations include:

- Uneven slit width
- Slight misalignment
- Unequal detector response
- Fabrication imperfections
- Unequal optical distance
- Thermal drift
- Vibration
- Residual detector memory
- Electromagnetic leakage

---

## Validation Procedures

### Left-Right Inversion Test

Rotate or mirror the apparatus.

If the effect follows the apparatus, it is likely a geometric artifact.

If the effect follows the recorded path history, it is more interesting.

---

### Symmetric Baseline Runs

Run the experiment with:

- No Path B enhancement
- Equal path lengths
- Weak marker off
- Identical detector settings

---

### Detector-Off Control

Run the same geometry with all which-path detectors off.

---

### Marker-Only Control

Run the weak marker on Path B without first-stage which-path detection.

---

### Randomised Path Enhancement Control

Randomly switch which side is enhanced.

This tests whether the bias follows Path B specifically or follows whichever path is enhanced.

---

# Experimental Controls

## Interaction Control

Use neutral particles where possible:

- Photons
- Neutrons
- Cold atoms

---

## Detector Isolation

Ensure detectors have:

- No afterglow
- No residual thermal signal
- No electromagnetic leakage
- No mechanical disturbance
- No persistent apparatus memory

---

## Timing Control

For two-particle experiments:

- Vary Δt between particles
- Test whether correlation decays with time separation

---

## Environmental Control

Stabilise:

- Temperature
- Vibration
- Air currents
- Electromagnetic fields
- Optical alignment

---

## Statistical Control

Use:

- Large sample sizes
- Predefined significance thresholds
- Blind analysis where possible
- Multiple runs
- Independent replication

---

# Significance

These experiments test whether quantum outcomes depend only on the current state, or whether prior measurement history and path enhancement can influence later probabilities.

---

## If Results Match Standard Quantum Mechanics

Then:

- No path memory is detected.
- No standalone entanglement-mediated influence is detected.
- No measurement-history accumulation is detected.
- Sequential slit systems behave consistently with standard state-update rules.

---

## If Results Show Bias

Then possible implications include:

- History-dependent behaviour
- Non-Markovian effects
- Path-specific memory or confidence
- Inter-particle correlation beyond expected independence
- Possible need to refine models of measurement, decoherence, or state evolution

---

# Summary

| Experiment | Tests | Standard Prediction | Hypothesis |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Single particle with Path B enhancement | No memory-based bias | Path memory / confidence |
| 2 | Two nearby particles | Independent behaviour | Sequential path correlation |
| 3 | Entangled pair, one observed | No standalone bias in B | Entanglement-mediated influence |
| 4 | Repeated observation then no observer | No dependence on N or sequence | Measurement-history conditioning |

---

# Final Question

> Do particles behave independently at each stage, or can prior measurement, path enhancement, entanglement, or measurement history influence future probabilities?

